# ScrapCo V2 — Frontend Requirements (Web)

## 1. Frontend Philosophy

The web application is:

- The SEO acquisition layer
- The seller-facing dashboard
- The vendor-facing dashboard (optional in Phase 1)
- The admin control panel

The web app must be:

- Server-rendered by default
- SEO-optimized
- Minimal client-side JavaScript
- Role-aware
- Performance-focused
- Lighthouse 90+ compliant

No SPA-only architecture.
No CSR-only design.
No heavy animation bloat.
No business logic in client.

---

## 2. Framework Requirements

Framework:
- Next.js (App Router)

Rendering:
- Server Components by default
- Client Components only when necessary
- SSR for dynamic pages
- Static generation for city pages
- Streaming where beneficial

No legacy Pages Router.

---

## 3. Core Web Surfaces

### 3.1 Marketing Site

Pages:

- Home
- How It Works
- Scrap Types & Rates
- City Pages (Narnaul, Gorakhpur, Singhana)
- About
- Contact
- FAQ
- Terms & Privacy

Must include:

- Metadata API usage
- Canonical URLs
- Open Graph tags
- Twitter meta
- JSON-LD structured data
- Sitemap generation
- Robots.txt

SEO is mandatory.

---

### 3.2 Seller Dashboard

Features:

- Create Pickup
- View Pickup Status
- Real-time status updates
- Transaction history
- Rating submission
- Profile management

Constraints:

- Must use authenticated SSR where possible
- Must not poll
- Must subscribe to real-time updates
- Must not expose internal DB fields

---

### 3.3 Vendor Dashboard

Features:

- View incoming offers
- Accept/Reject offer
- View assigned pickups
- Update pickup status
- Capacity overview
- Earnings summary (Phase 2)

Real-time updates mandatory.

No polling.

---

### 3.4 Admin Dashboard

Features:

- Manage scrap types
- Manage scrap rates
- View region metrics
- View pickup analytics
- Commission configuration
- Vendor management

Must require ADMIN role.
No env-based bypass.

---

## 4. Routing Structure

Example App Router structure:

```

app/
├── page.tsx
├── city/
│   ├── [slug]/
│   │   └── page.tsx
├── dashboard/
│   ├── seller/
│   ├── vendor/
│   ├── admin/
├── pickup/
│   ├── [id]/
│   │   └── page.tsx

```

Role-based access enforced in layout.

---

## 5. SEO Requirements

Each public page must:

- Define title
- Define description
- Define canonical URL
- Define Open Graph metadata
- Include JSON-LD schema

Structured data:

- LocalBusiness
- Service
- FAQ
- Breadcrumb

Sitemap must include:

- All city pages
- Scrap type pages
- Static marketing pages

No blank SSR pages.

---

## 6. Performance Requirements

Targets:

- Lighthouse Performance > 90
- Accessibility > 90
- SEO > 95
- Best Practices > 95

Constraints:

- No unnecessary client components
- No heavy animation libraries globally
- No large icon bundles
- Use dynamic imports for heavy components
- Optimize images via next/image
- No blocking scripts

---

## 7. State Management

Use:

- Server state first
- SWR for client caching
- Minimal Context usage
- No Redux
- No global provider re-render cascade

Avoid:

- Polling
- setInterval
- Massive global state trees

---

## 8. Authentication Handling

Use:

- Supabase Auth
- JWT in HTTP-only cookie OR secure storage
- Server-side session validation
- Role-based routing guards

No localStorage-based auth without validation.

---

## 9. UI/UX Standards

Design must:

- Be clean and minimal
- Be responsive (mobile-first)
- Support keyboard navigation
- Support screen readers
- Respect prefers-reduced-motion
- Meet WCAG AA contrast

No inaccessible components.

---

## 10. Form Handling

Forms must:

- Use Zod schema validation
- Display inline validation errors
- Prevent duplicate submissions
- Support loading states
- Support error states

All errors must use standardized API error format.

---

## 11. Real-Time Integration

Seller dashboard must:

- Subscribe to pickup-specific events
- Update UI instantly on status change

Vendor dashboard must:

- Subscribe to offer events
- Reflect assignment instantly

No polling allowed.

---

## 12. Security Constraints

Frontend must:

- Never expose service-role key
- Never expose HMAC secret
- Never embed sensitive environment variables
- Never allow admin route without role check
- Never trust client role claim

All sensitive logic must be server-side.

---

## 13. Code Structure Requirements

Use feature-based structure:

```

features/
├── pickup/
├── vendor/
├── admin/
├── auth/
├── shared/

```

Shared components in:

```

components/

```

Shared utilities in:

```

lib/

```

No mixed folder chaos.

---

## 14. Error Handling

Frontend must:

- Use error boundaries
- Display meaningful fallback UI
- Log errors to monitoring service
- Avoid crashing entire app on minor failure

---

## 15. Accessibility Requirements

Must include:

- aria-label on interactive elements
- Focus trapping in modals
- Keyboard navigable navigation
- Skip-to-content link
- Semantic HTML
- Proper heading hierarchy

Accessibility score must exceed 90.

---

## 16. Internationalization (Future-Ready)

Architecture must allow:

- Multi-language support
- Region-based language expansion
- Currency formatting per region

Do not hardcode text strings inline in components.

---

## 17. Analytics Integration

Must support:

- Event tracking
- Conversion tracking
- Page-level metrics
- Pickup creation funnel tracking

Analytics must not block rendering.

---

## 18. Guardrails

Web frontend must never:

- Depend on client-side business logic
- Poll backend for status
- Render blank SSR pages
- Use wildcard CORS
- Store secrets in bundle
- Depend on environment flag auth

---

## 19. Summary

Web frontend must be:

- SEO-first
- Server-rendered
- Role-aware
- Real-time integrated
- Secure
- Accessible
- Performant
- Scalable

It is both acquisition engine and marketplace interface.

No compromises allowed.
```
